# Clinic Genie Frontend Architecture Rules

## Tech Stack

Client: Clinic Genie  
Tech Stack: Next.js, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, Framer Motion  
Deployment: Vercel  

Use this stack consistently unless explicitly instructed otherwise.

## Tailwind CSS and Design System Rules

Strictly follow the Tailwind configuration.

Use design tokens from the Tailwind config for colours, spacing, typography, radius, shadows, and layout.

Do not use arbitrary values unless absolutely necessary and justified by an existing design limitation.

Correct:

```tsx
className="text-clinic-primary bg-clinic-soft rounded-clinic"
```

Avoid:

```tsx
className="text-[#0052CC] bg-[#F7FAFF] rounded-[18px]"
```

Use consistent spacing across sections.

Avoid random one off spacing values.

Use a clean visual hierarchy with generous whitespace, strong typographic rhythm, and clear section separation.

## Next.js Rules

Use Next.js App Router conventions unless the existing project structure requires otherwise.

Prefer server components by default.

Use client components only when needed for:

- Framer Motion animation
- Browser APIs
- Local state
- Interactive forms
- Event handlers
- Hooks that require the client

Add `"use client"` only when necessary.

Use `next/link` for internal navigation.

Use `next/image` for images unless there is a specific technical reason not to.

Always define image dimensions or use a layout that prevents Cumulative Layout Shift.

Use metadata appropriately for SEO.

Keep route level files clean and delegate UI to reusable sections and components.

Avoid unnecessary client side JavaScript.

## TypeScript and React Rules

Use strict TypeScript.

Do not use `any`.

If a type is genuinely unknown, use `unknown` and narrow it safely.

Use functional React components.

Define clear prop interfaces or types.

Example:

```tsx
interface ServiceCardProps {
  title: string;
  description: string;
  href: string;
  icon?: React.ReactNode;
}
```

Define rigorous types for:

- Navigation items
- Service data
- Specialty cards
- Case studies
- Blog articles
- CTA blocks
- Form values
- API responses
- Animation variants
- SEO metadata
- Clinic related content structures
- Genie motif content blocks where relevant

Use explicit return types where they improve clarity.

Keep components small and single responsibility.

Avoid large monolithic components.

Prefer composition over deeply nested conditional UI.

## File and Folder Structure Rules

Use a clear modular structure.

Reusable UI primitives:

```txt
/components/ui
```

Examples:

```txt
Button.tsx
Card.tsx
Input.tsx
Textarea.tsx
Modal.tsx
Badge.tsx
SectionWrapper.tsx
Container.tsx
```

Page sections:

```txt
/components/sections
```

Examples:

```txt
HeroSection.tsx
WhyClinicGenieSection.tsx
ServicesSection.tsx
SpecialtiesSection.tsx
ClinicGenieAdvantageSection.tsx
SelectedWorkSection.tsx
HowWeWorkSection.tsx
InsightsSection.tsx
FinalCTASection.tsx
```

Feature specific components:

```txt
/components/features
```

Examples:

```txt
orb
case-studies
insights
specialties
contact
genie-motif
```

Shared data:

```txt
/data
```

Examples:

```txt
navigation.ts
services.ts
specialties.ts
case-studies.ts
insights.ts
brand-copy.ts
```

Shared utilities:

```txt
/lib
```

Examples:

```txt
utils.ts
seo.ts
constants.ts
schema.ts
```

Hooks:

```txt
/hooks
```

Examples:

```txt
useReducedMotionPreference.ts
useIsMobile.ts
```

Do not duplicate data across components.

If content is reused, move it into a typed data file.

## Component Quality Rules

Before creating a new component, check whether an existing reusable component can be used or extended.

Components should be:

- Small
- Typed
- Reusable where practical
- Easy to scan
- Accessible
- Responsive
- Aligned with the design system

Avoid deeply nested JSX.

Avoid mixing unrelated concerns in one component.

Keep presentation, data, and logic reasonably separated.

Use clear prop names.

Avoid vague names such as `Box`, `Thing`, `ContentBlock2`, or `NewSection`.

## Forms and Data Handling Rules

Treat all submitted form data carefully.

Validate form inputs on both client and server.

Do not rely only on frontend sanitisation.

Use clear loading, success, and error states.

Do not log sensitive user submitted information to the console.

Do not expose private information in client components.

Do not store sensitive information unnecessarily in local state, local storage, or session storage.

Use accessible error messages.

Ensure form fields have:

- Visible labels
- Clear placeholders where helpful
- Error messages
- Valid input types
- Autocomplete attributes where appropriate

For contact or strategy call forms, keep the experience simple, trustworthy, and low friction.

## Environment Variable and Security Rules

This project deploys to Vercel.

Use environment variables through `process.env`.

Never expose API keys, private endpoints, tokens, or secrets to the browser.

Only use `NEXT_PUBLIC_` variables for values that are intentionally safe to expose publicly.

Do not hardcode credentials.

Do not commit secret keys.

Do not print environment variables in logs.

When adding integrations, keep server side logic server side.

## Error Handling Rules

Handle errors clearly and calmly.

Use user friendly error messages.

Avoid exposing technical details to users.

For forms, explain what went wrong and what the user can do next.

Do not silently fail.

## AI Behaviour Rules

When generating new code:

- Follow the existing project structure
- Use TypeScript
- Use Tailwind design tokens
- Use Framer Motion for animation
- Avoid `any`
- Avoid arbitrary Tailwind values
- Avoid unnecessary dependencies
- Keep components modular
- Use semantic HTML
- Preserve the Clinic Genie tone and motif rules
- Use British English
- Do not use em dashes

When editing existing code:

- Preserve existing naming conventions where sensible
- Preserve existing design tokens
- Preserve the approved layout direction
- Refactor only when it improves clarity, maintainability, accessibility, or performance
- Do not introduce unrelated changes
- Do not rewrite entire files unnecessarily
- Explain meaningful structural changes through clear code organisation

## Non Negotiables

Do not use `any`.

Do not leak environment variables.

Do not use arbitrary Tailwind values unless absolutely necessary.

Do not add dependencies without a clear reason.

Do not ignore mobile behaviour.

Do not use em dashes.
